_source.dataProvider: Dudley Observatory

creator: Fullam, Ernest F.
sourceResource.description: Raw footage of the creation of a Venus Flytrap rocket by unidentified lab technicians. No sound. Scenes: :02-:10 - Technicians working on a crate containing a wrapped rocket nose cone. :11-:44 - Technicians constructing the internal structure of the rocket nose cone. Figure in the back right, leaning against the corner counter, is Dudley Observatory director Curtis Hemenway. :45-1:52 - Technician builds the collectors that will be housed in the nosecone which will collect micrometeorites. 1:53-2:45 Shots of an airplane taking off from an unknown airstrip. Presumably the plane is headed to Sweden where the rocket will be launched.
relation: Dudley Observatory Historical Archives;
sourceResource.rights: This digital image may be used for educational uses. Please cite as Dudley Observatory. Prior written permission is required for any other use of the images from the Dudley Observatory.
title: Preparation and Shipping of a Venus Flytrap Rocket

creator: Krasniewicz, Louise
sourceResource.description: Delaware Avenue: Recalling the Early Days is a slideshow originally produced in the 1980s by Louise Krasniewicz for Albany Public Library and digitized in 2014 for APL's digital collection on New York Heritage. Oral histories from former residents of the Delaware Avenue neighborhood are paired with images that span the late 19th century to the mid 20th century. The development of the area from a somewhat rural section of the city to a more connected, urban neighborhood is discussed. The narrators reminisce about it was like to live there as children, and they also discuss the expansion of the trolley car system, various churches, and their perceptions of the people who lived there.
format: MPEG-4 video in color and black & white, 18:09 length

sourceResource.description: A short documentary that aired on WMHT in Schenectady in 1966. It features Curtis Hemenway, director of the Dudley Observatory from 1956-1977. Hemenway gives a thirty minutes lecture on three different types of collections experiments that involve sampling materials from very high altitudes. During the first thirteen minutes, Hemenway describes the properties of micrometeorites, or space dust, the process for collecting it from the upper atmosphere and the implications for aerospace travel. He then explains a similar set of experiments dealing with noctilucent clouds; extremely high altitude clouds found at the poles. At the 18:30 mark, Hemenway demonstrates a balloon collector which is used to collect larger particles than the previous two experiments, such as particles from meteors.

creator: SUNY Albany Educational Communications Center
sourceResource.description: A short documentary about the construction of the Frank L. Fullam Radio Telescope at Bolton Landing. The documentary begins with a capsule history of the Dudley Observatory, hitting the high notes of the Observatory's past. At the 1:30 mark it reaches the Curtis Hemenway years, and at the 1:53 mark it begins talking about the radio telescope. The documentary covers the telescope donation by the Carnegie Foundation and its reconstruction until the 8:00 mark, then finishes out by explaining the research performed by the telescope.

creator: Langley Research Center
sourceResource.description: A short documentary about NASA's Project S-55 produced by the Langley Research Center. Project S-55 was a NASA attempt to gauge the frequency and nature of "space dust" or micrometeorites. The film begins be explaining the problems that space dust creates for space exploration. At the 3:00 minute mark the discussion moves to Project S-55, the launching of a satellite that would measure space dust. The actual launch occurs at 23:00.
